The `Uncaught TypeError: el is null` error is likely occurring because the `id` variable is not being properly passed to the `addElementBar` function for some nodes.

To fix the error and ensure that all nodes are properly created, you can modify the code as follows:

```javascript
var addElementBar = function(id) {
    var radioBarContainer = document.getElementById("radio-bar-menu");

    var div = document.createElement('div');

    div.innerHTML = `<input type="radio" id="${id}" name="radio-group" />
    <label for="${id}">${id}</label>
    <br><br>`;
    radioBarContainer.appendChild(div);

    var el = document.getElementById(id);
    if (el) { // Check if element with the provided id exists
        el.addEventListener('click', function() {
            console.log(id);
            filterNode("id", id);
        });
    }
};

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    s.graph.nodes().forEach(function(node) {
        addElementBar(node.id);
    });
});
```

In this updated code, a check is added before attaching the event listener to the `el` element. If the element with the provided `id` does not exist, the event listener will not be added, preventing the "el is null" error from occurring.

Using a non-async loop like a regular `for` loop may not directly solve the "el is null" error. The error occurs when the `getElementById` method does not find an element with the provided `id`. Using a non-async loop will affect the order of execution, but it won't change the fact that the element is not present in the DOM.

However, if the issue is related to the timing of the `DOMContentLoaded` event, using a non-async loop may help. By using a non-async loop, the `addElementBar` function will be called synchronously for each node, ensuring that all nodes are created before the `DOMContentLoaded` event is fired.

Here's an example of using a non-async `for` loop to call `addElementBar`:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    var nodes = s.graph.nodes();
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        addElementBar(nodes[i].id);
    }
});
```

By using a non-async `for` loop, the `addElementBar` function will be called for each node sequentially, which may prevent any unexpected timing issues that could lead to the "el is null" error.

The menu that expands when clicked, containing some fields and data, is typically called an "accordion" or a "collapsible menu."

Accordion menus or collapsible menus allow users to expand and collapse sections within a menu to show or hide additional content. This behavior is commonly used to organize and present information in a compact and intuitive way.

You can create an accordion menu using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<div class="accordion">
  <div class="accordion-item">
    <div class="accordion-header">Menu Item 1</div>
    <div class="accordion-content">
      <!-- Content for Menu Item 1 -->
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="accordion-item">
    <div class="accordion-header">Menu Item 2</div>
    <div class="accordion-content">
      <!-- Content for Menu Item 2 -->
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Add more menu items as needed -->
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.accordion-header {
  cursor: pointer;
}

.accordion-content {
  display: none;
}

.accordion-item.active .accordion-content {
  display: block;
}
```

JavaScript/jQuery:
```javascript
$(document).ready(function () {
  $('.accordion-header').click(function () {
    $(this).parent('.accordion-item').toggleClass('active');
  });
});
```

In the above code, each menu item consists of an accordion header (the part that is clicked) and an accordion content (the part that expands and collapses). The CSS hides the accordion content by default (`display: none`), and only shows the content when the associated accordion header is clicked and the corresponding accordion item is given the `active` class (`display: block`).

The JavaScript code adds a click event listener to each accordion header using jQuery. When a header is clicked, the parent accordion item is toggled between active and inactive states, which triggers the CSS class change.

You will need to customize the HTML and add your own content for each menu item in order to display the desired fields and data within the accordion content.

I apologize for the confusion. In Sigma.js, the `repulsion` parameter is not directly configurable through the `config` method. Instead, the repulsion force can be adjusted by modifying the `forceAtlas2Settings` object and then applying it to the layout algorithm.

Here's an example of how you can adjust the repulsion force in Sigma.js:

```javascript
s.cameras[0].graph.nodes().forEach(function(node) {
  // Increase the repulsion force for each node
  node.settings('forceAtlas2Settings', { 
    nodeDistance: 200 // Adjust the desired repulsion force here
  });
});

// Refresh the layout after modifying the repulsion force
s.refresh();
```

In the above code, we are accessing each node in the graph using the `cameras[0].graph.nodes()` function. Then, we set the `forceAtlas2Settings` for each node using the `settings` method. Adjust the `nodeDistance` value to control the repulsion force between nodes. A higher value will result in a stronger repulsion force.

Finally, call `refresh` on the Sigma instance (`s`) to update the layout based on the modified repulsion force.

